Description: Fast, scalable linkage disequilibrium (LD) block detection for
    genome-wide SNP data. Supports two LD metrics: standard r^2 (fast,
    suitable for 10M+ markers) and the kinship-adjusted rV^2 (Mangin et al.
    2012, Heredity 108(3):285-291) for structured or related populations.
    The clique-based Big-LD segmentation algorithm (Kim et al. 2018,
    Bioinformatics 34(4):588-596) is accelerated by Rcpp/RcppArmadillo and
    OpenMP. A unified multi-format I/O layer reads numeric dosage CSV,
    HapMap, VCF, SNPRelate GDS, and PLINK BED files through a streaming
    never-full-genome memory model. Downstream modules cover: haplotype
    phasing (statistical via Beagle or
    pre-phased VCF); haplotype extraction for phased and unphased data;
    diversity metrics (richness, Nei's expected heterozygosity corrected for
    sample size, Shannon entropy, effective number of alleles, sweep flag);
    post-GWAS QTL region definition with pleiotropic block detection;
    haplotype feature matrices for genomic prediction (additive 0/1/2/NA
    for phased or 0/1/NA for unphased data, or binary presence/absence 0/1
    encoding); and output writers for numeric dosage matrices, nucleotide
    character matrices with IUPAC ambiguity codes, and diversity CSV formats
    compatible with rrBLUP, BGLR, and ASReml-R.
    A complete haplotype-based genomic prediction pipeline implements the
    Tong et al. (2025, Theor Appl Genet 138:267) haplotype stacking
    methodology via run_haplotype_prediction(), which accepts a single trait
    or multiple traits simultaneously. All traits are fitted using
    rrBLUP::kin.blup() in a per-trait loop sharing a single trait-agnostic
    GRM, making cross-trait block importance values directly comparable.
    Block importance is aggregated across traits (mean scaled variance,
    n_traits_important, important_any, important_all) for robust haplotype
    stacking candidate identification.
    Ten additional analysis functions extend the pipeline: k-fold
    cross-validation for genomic prediction accuracy estimation
    (cv_haplotype_prediction); between-population allele frequency and FST
    comparison per block (compare_haplotype_populations); minimum-spanning
    haplotype network visualisation via igraph (plot_haplotype_network);
    Finlay-Wilkinson stability analysis across environments
    (run_haplotype_stability); candidate region export to BED, CSV, or
    biomaRt format (export_candidate_regions); per-allele effect
    decomposition from SNP effects (decompose_block_effects); sliding-window
    genome-wide diversity scan (scan_diversity_windows); true gametic
    diplotype inference from phased or unphased input
    (infer_block_haplotypes); rare-allele collapsing with three strategies
    (collapse_haplotypes); and cross-panel haplotype label harmonisation
    via reference-dictionary matching (harmonize_haplotypes).
    Five haplotype association and breeding decision functions complete the
    inference layer: block-level haplotype association testing via a unified
    Q+K mixed linear model with vectorised per-allele scan and simpleM
    multiple-testing correction (test_block_haplotypes, Gao et al. 2008
    Genet Epidemiol 32:361; sig_metric selects among p_wald, p_fdr,
    p_simplem, p_simplem_sidak; all four p-value columns always present;
    meff_scope controls Meff estimation at chromosome, global, or block level);
    diplotype effect estimation with additive/dominance decomposition and
    overdominance detection (estimate_diplotype_effects); genome-wide
    haplotype portfolio scoring against known allele effects with a normalised
    stacking index (score_favorable_haplotypes); a per-parent allele inventory
    for haplotype stacking cross decisions (summarize_parent_haplotypes); and
    cross-population haplotype effect concordance via IVW meta-analysis,
    Cochran Q heterogeneity, I-squared inconsistency, and direction agreement
    (compare_block_effects); cross-population concordance from external GWAS
    results produced by any tool (compare_gwas_effects; accepts raw GWAS data
    frames or define_qtl_regions() output; derives SE from z-score when absent).
    Both concordance functions support block_match = 'position' to match LD
    blocks by genomic interval overlap (Intersection-over-Union) rather than by
    block_id string equality, handling the common case where block boundaries
    differ between populations due to different ancestral LD structures. The
    match_type output column reports 'exact', 'position' (IoU >= overlap_min,
    default 0.50), or 'pop1_only' for every block.
    LD decay analysis (compute_ld_decay) estimates the distance at which r2
    or rV2 drops below a critical threshold per chromosome, using a
    memory-efficient position-first random sampling strategy and optional
    Hill-Weir (1988) nonlinear or LOESS curve fitting. Chromosome-specific
    decay distances can be passed to define_qtl_regions() to replace fixed
    block boundaries with LD-aware candidate gene windows around GWAS hits.
    Six example datasets are shipped in data/: ldx_geno, ldx_snp_info,
    ldx_blocks, ldx_gwas, ldx_blues (pre-adjusted BLUEs for two traits), and
    ldx_blues_list (per-environment BLUEs for stability analysis examples).
    The pipeline also includes: VanRaden GRM from haplotype features
    (compute_haplotype_grm); backsolved per-SNP effects
    (backsolve_snp_effects, Tong et al. 2025); local haplotype GEBV per
    block (compute_local_gebv, Tong et al. 2024, Theor Appl Genet 137:274);
    and unified block ranking across three evidence layers — GWAS hits,
    trait variance, and haplotype diversity — via rank_haplotype_blocks and
    integrate_gwas_haplotypes. Automatic parameter tuning against GWAS
    marker coverage is provided via tune_LD_params. Three acceleration
    features target WGS-scale panels: Louvain/Leiden community detection
    (polynomial-time alternative to Bron-Kerbosch clique enumeration via
    CLQmode = 'Louvain' or 'Leiden'); sparse LD restricted to SNP pairs
    within a physical distance window (max_bp_distance, implemented in
    compute_r2_sparse_cpp); and a file-backed memory-mapped genotype store
    via bigmemory (read_geno_bigmemory) that keeps peak RAM proportional
    to accessed columns rather than the full matrix.
